Molecular diversity of dragonflies in three high‐elevation Andean tropical lakes through DNA barcoding

Rodrigo Chiriboga‐Ortega
Christine Van der Heyden
Maria Eugenia Sulen Burgos
Sania Ortega
Tania Oña
Elizabeth Velarde
Peter Goethals
Alonzo Alfaro‐Núñez
First published: 15 February 2021
https://doi.org/10.1111/btp.12927

Associate Editor: Tomás A. Carlo

Handling Editor:: Alexander Smith

Funding information:

This research work was partially funded by VLIR‐UOS South Initiative ZEIN 2014Z155.

Abstract

enThis link goes to a English sectionesThis link goes to a Spanish section

Genetic and morphological identification of dragonflies' larvae species in three high‐elevation Andean tropical lakes was done using DNA barcoding of the cytochrome oxidase 1 gene (COI). Phylogeny allowed inferring the evolutionary relationships of at least five species (from 74 samples) that belong to two different families within the Odonata order.

Abstract in Spanish is available with online material.

Andean tropical lakes (ATL) are of extreme value for understanding the past, the present, and the future of these delicate high‐elevation environments. Because of their high elevation, ATL are exposed to intense solar radiation that remains constant throughout the year in the equator (Aguilera et al., 2006), suffering nevertheless, large fluctuations of temperature during a single day. Biodiversity in tropical mountains, and in particular in the Andes around the Equator, is particularly rich and high with approximately 25% of the diversity from all land area on Earth (Rahbek et al., 2019b). Moreover, it has been well documented that hot spots in the tropical Andean mountains, including water reservoirs and lakes, can hold higher diversity than wet lowland (Rahbek et al., 2019a).

Despite being in the so‐called “hot spots” of diversity and among the most threatened habitats on the planet, ATL are ecosystems not yet studied at depth and our knowledge and understanding of high‐elevation lentic ecosystems and genetic composition of macroinvertebrates are still limited (Aguilera et al., 2006; Barta et al., 2018; Van Colen et al., 2017). Moreover, these environments have been experiencing a decline in biodiversity due to climate change and anthropogenic activities.

Projections for the tropical Andean climate suggest an overall increase of temperature by the end of the 21st century (Urrutia & Vuille, 2009). Climate change and anthropogenic activities can cause major changes in the water chemistry of lentic ecosystems, which in turn may have repercussions on its biodiversity including macroinvertebrates diversity.

Odonates are among the most iconic and well‐characterized group of macroinvertebrates widely distributed in freshwater sources including streams, wetlands, and lakes. They have complex, biphasic lifestyles. Dragonflies and damselflies are considered as a suitable group of insects for ecological and evolutionary studies, and they are a key group for comparative studies on insect and arthropod evolution (Kalkman et al., 2007). Furthermore, they are well suited as a bioindicator for environmental quality disturbance. In addition, many species display species‐specific habitat requirements and disturbances in environmental variables have been shown to influence the patterns of species assemblages (Osborn, 2005). Changes in environmental variables in lakes such as ambient temperature, water chemistry, and the presence/absence of different types of vegetation that affect dragonflies diversity, richness, and abundance may most likely be driven by continuous sediment load and habitat homogeneity (de Oliveira‐Junior et al., 2015; Miguel et al., 2017). However, there is still a lack of information and studies regarding the importance and potential use of odonates as bioindicators of lentic ecosystems in the Neotropics.

As such, little information is found regarding species diversity in Africa and Latin America, and in particular across the Neotropical regions (Bybee et al., 2016; Kalkman et al., 2007) for example ATL. Despite the recent advance of high‐throughput sequencing technologies, the missing gap of biological information along with the limited amount of genomic data available for Odonata compared to other insect groups prevents the scientific community from filling the holes in understanding insect evolutionary histories (Bybee et al., 2016).

This research study aimed for the molecular identification of Odonata species in three lakes of high elevation (lakes: Yahuarcocha, San Pablo and Caricocha) ranging from 2200 to over 3700 meters above sea level (m.a.s.l) in the Northern part of Ecuador. The COI DNA barcode was used for the molecular identification of dragonflies which is indispensable to establish and determine a biological indicator for the ecological water quality in these unique ecosystems. We collected a total of 74 larval specimens near the shore of the lakes, which were morphologically identified and distributed into two families: 42 in Coenagrionidae and 32 in Aeshnidae. Total genomic DNA was extracted from head and legs from each sample. Thereafter, DNA fragments were amplified by PCR and were subsequently Sanger sequenced (see Appendix S1 for detailed information of the sampling and methodology protocol).

In our study, despite the limited number of samples obtained and analyzed, the identification process by DNA barcodes allowed to discover of at least two branches that have not been reported before, as they do not match any previous record available in online databases. This allows us to demonstrate that, with a simple monitoring and identification process, it is possible to discover and report potential unknown species in the study areas, which may be exposed to diverse environmental or anthropogenic factors that could have a direct effect on these populations.

The COI sequences obtained from each individual were processed and only 16% (12 sequences) of the ID results (see Figure 1) were not congruent with the molecular identification, as records were not found in databases. The identification of specimens based on morphology might be challenging if only taxonomic standard keys are applied, but if in addition, online‐public databases such as GenBank (NCBI) or The Barcode of Life Data System BOLD (Ratnasingham & Hebert, 2007) are used for this purpose, correct identification increases in a 10‐fold. However, it is important to keep in mind that primary online databases may be composed of experimental results that may not represent the entire biodiversity majority. Therefore, it is highly possible that public databases, sometimes, do not include sequences of species of interest, and as such, it may create statistical bias in correctly naming the exact species.

We reconstructed a phylogenetic tree using DNA sequences obtained from the sampled Odonata specimens and reference sequences. The phylogenetic relationships allowed the clustering of 74 sequences into five groups (see Figure 2). Morphological analyses of specimens support this taxonomic classification. The presence of Rhionaeschna marchali and Rhionaeschna elsia has been previously confirmed in Equatorial Andean water areas (Cordero et al., 2016). The distribution of Remartinia luteipennis and Ischnura ramburii was also confirmed by the IUCN (International Union for Conservation of Nature and Natural Resources) report published of the Red List of Threatened Species (IUCN, 2006, 2007), where these two species appeared as threatened also in Equatorial Andean aquatic areas.

This is the first study of its kind carried out in the region, establishing the path for further research in the applications of DNA barcoding. The Odonata species identified in this work have been previously used as bioindicators. Rhionaeschna marchali and Rhionaeschna elsia were used as study models to determine the impact of climate change on the dispersion and population dynamics of dragonflies in the Peruvian Andes (Hoffmann, 2010). Remartinia luteipennis was identified in the restoration of a wetland in Mexico (Anaya & Novelo, 2015), and Ischnura ramburii as a bioindicator of the quality of the lake habitat in Louisiana, United States (Osborn, 2005).

The relevance of Odonata as taxonomic group for monitoring biological water quality is reflected in the advantages that it possesses over conventional methods for environmental quality assessments. The study of Odonates has allowed the evaluation of the grazing effects on Canadian prairie wetlands (Lee Foote & Rice Hornung, 2005), the assessment of habitat suitability (Harabiš & Dolný, 2012), and to determine environmental impacts in streams in the eastern Brazilian Amazon (de Oliveira‐Junior et al., 2015). Also, the comparison of adult and larvae responses is a valuable indicator of shallow lake restoration (D'Amico et al., 2004) and the examination of changes in both Odonata species diversity and number of individuals has shown to be effective to evaluate the improvement of water quality in sewage ponds (Catling, 2005).

As for the Andean lakes analyzed in this study, firstly, the Yahuarcocha Lake is a relatively large, turbid, shallow and moderately eutrophic lake suffering from cyanobacteria blooms. This lake is also surrounded by human settlements and a relatively high amount of human activities (e.g., hotels, racetracks, and sport activities). Although its high elevation, the mean temperature of the water is relatively warm‐high (21°C). This is caused by solar radiation heating faster during the day than the cooling at night. This is a well‐known fact noted in other tropical mountain lakes, such as the nearby lake San Pablo (Van Colen et al., 2017). San Pablo Lake is the second largest lake in Ecuador. Agricultural activities, erosion of the lake basin, and the lack of treatment of wastewater have caused a high eutrophication of the lake (Casallas & Gunkel, 2002). Finally, Caricocha, the most natural and undisturbed, located at the highest elevation of the lakes was analyzed in this study. Caricocha should be considered as a lake of paramount importance for the local biodiversity and as a natural water source. However, there are no data on the diversity of macroinvertebrates in this lake ecosystem.

In accordance with the number of taxonomic groups detected, the lake with the highest detected Odonata biodiversity was Yahuarcocha with four potential species of odonates identified. Rhionaeschna marchali species was the only species of dragonfly present in all three lakes. Rhionaeschna elsia, Ischnura ramburii, and Remartinia luteipennis were present only in Yahuarcocha. One species from San Pablo Lake could not be identified.

At least five species of odonates were found present for the three different Andean lakes analyzed. Based on the records available at GenBank and BOLD databases (see Figure 1), we concluded that there is potentially at least one branch cluster of specimens of the tree not described before, as one branch group of sequences in the tree did not match with any previous species records of the BOLD (https://www.boldsystems.org/) and GenBank (https://blast.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/Blast.cgi) databases. We obtained matches for four different species of BOLD database, and three of GenBank (NCBI). Rhionaeschna marchali obtained sequences were submitted at the two databases. Despite the fact that more than 400 species of dragonflies have been reported for this entire region, only eight species have been provided with adequate molecular background (Mauffray & Tennessen, 2019; Ratnasingham & Hebert, 2007). While Remartinia luteipennis and Ischnura ramburii are the most distributed species in equatorial Andes (IUCN, 2007; IUCN, 2006), Rhionaeschna marchali has been rarely observed in ponds and lakes (IUCN, 2006). There is very limited information about the ecology and distribution of Rhionaeschna elsia in this region (Mauffray & Tennessen, 2019).

This is the first report of macroinvertebrates species registered in the Caricocha Lake. Despite the fact that Caricocha is the lake at the highest elevation and with the less human influence, we were unable to discover a new species of dragonfly via this investigation. Only one species, previously described, was detected at this particular spot. A possible explanation to the low diversity detected may be linked to the temperature variable and seasonality of the life cycle. Temperature can induce substantial changes in the habitat and the biological interactions between the study organisms with plants and predators (Córdoba‐Aguilar, 2008; Realpe, 2009). The lake with the lowest human influence but the highest elevation (more than 1000 m higher than the other selected lakes) showed the lowest diversity of dragonfly species.

As such, based on our results, we cannot associate or relate anthropogenic activities as a direct ecological stressor for low the diversity detected in this taxonomic group. We conclude that the low number of individuals collected in this study is the main reason for the low number of recordings of dragonfly species.

High altitude Andean lakes are neglected areas, yet extremely important environments for biodiversity and as freshwater reservoirs. Identifying, studying, and using bioindicator species of macroinvertebrates, such as dragonflies, could allow us to elucidate the diversity and the suspected anthropogenic damage that these delicate environments are exposed. By applying affordable molecular tools as DNA barcoding and phylogenetics, we could establish a procedure for future ecological and biodiversity studies of Odonates that can be more widely applied to investigate and assess the diversity of these lakes. Further studies are needed with larger samples and a spatial–temporal collection covering the collection of dragonflies in different life stages in order to provide more accurate data for the conservation in environmentally threatened areas and the rehabilitation of anthropogenically disturbed zones.
